  "augment.chat.userGuidelines": "# Source Code Editing Guidelines\n\nFollow these rules to ensure consistency, maintain behavior, and adhere to the **Minimal Changes Principle**.\n\n## General Principles\n\n### 1. **Minimal Changes Principle**\n\n- **Definition:** Make only the smallest necessary changes to achieve the goal while preserving existing functionality, behavior, and structure.\n- **Examples of Allowed Changes:**\n  - Fixing specific errors or bugs without altering unrelated code.\n  - Adding error handling or safeguards directly relevant to the fix.\n  - Adjusting configurations like timeouts or retry attempts if explicitly required for the fix.\n- **Examples of Disallowed Changes:**\n  - Removing unrelated tests or functionality.\n  - Refactoring code beyond the scope of the fix.\n  - Introducing new features or logic unless explicitly requested.\n- **Response Example:**\n\n  ```text\n  Let me make the smallest possible change to resolve the issue while preserving all existing functionality and test behavior.\n  ```\n\n### 2. **Accountability for Changes**\n\n- Clearly explain any deletions or large modifications before applying them.\n- Ensure that all removed or altered functionality is explicitly justified as necessary to resolve the issue.\n\n### 3. **Consistency and Alignment**\n\n- **Understand first the complete codebase and its structure, not just the specific issue!**\n- **Always understand the complete module when you plan to make changes.**\n- Always understand the project structure and context before proposing fixes or improvements.\n- Follow the **red-green testing approach**:\n  - Add failing tests for issues before fixing them.\n  - Fix the code until the tests pass.\n- Use the **Minimal Changes Principle** to resolve issues while keeping changes focused and isolated.\n\n## Verification Rules\n\n- Justify all additions/deletions\n- Verify:\n  - Preserved functionality\n  - Limited scope\n  - Explained major changes\n- Pre-apply:\n  - Changes needed\n  - Why needed\n  - Behavior intact\n\n## Code Changes Rules\n\n1. Identify the specific issue(s).\n2. Plan the changes with minimal impact.\n3. Justify all changes before applying them.\n4. Make changes, adhering strictly to the \"Minimal Changes Principle.\"\n5. Summarize changes, highlighting how they address the issue without altering functionality.\n\n### Guidelines for Bugs, Tests, or Errors\n\n- Solve only the specific issue(s) while maintaining the existing functionality, adjust or write tests accordingly.\n- Do not remove or simplify existing tests unless explicitly necessary.\n\n### Guidelines for TypeScript Type Errors\n\n- Only resolve TypeScript error(s)!\n- Avoid modifying logic or unrelated code!\n- Check the existing type definitions in the codebase and type assertions!\n- For detailed type analysis steps and guidelines, refer to Memory[43fff0bd-cbff-4fa6-be89-e88161bc1b36] \"1. TypeScript Development Guidelines\"\n\n## Command Generation Keywords (`CGK`)\n\n1. Specify target path after keyword\n2. Use absolute paths as needed\n3. Include file permissions if necessary\n4. Use heredoc (<< 'EOL') for multi-line content\n5. Add execution permissions automatically for scripts\n\n### Commands\n\n```shell\ncat > script-name.sh << 'EOL'\n#!/bin/bash\n[script content]\nEOL\n\nchmod +x script-name.sh\n```\n\n## Patch Rules\n\n- **Paths**: Root-relative.\n- **LF**: Unix.\n- **Changes**: One/patch.\n- **Context**: 3 lines.\n- **Files**: Blank line between.\n- **Format**: `diff --git a/<file> b/<file> --- a/<file> +++ b/<file> @@ -<start,count> +<start,count> @@ <context> -<old> +<new> <context>`\n\n## Markdown Rules\n\n### Structure\n\n- Start with h1 (#), proper header hierarchy\n- Blank lines around headers, lists, code blocks\n- Intend: 2-spaces\n- Align table pipes\n- No blanks between list items\n- Use **bold** for emphasis\n- Use `code` for inline code\n- Consistent indentation\n- One topic per section\n- Use ``` for outer blocks\n- Use tildes (~~~) for:\n  - Nested code blocks inside markdown\n  - Each deeper level adds one more tilde\n- Add language tag after fence\n\n## Tool Usage and Flow Action Credit Guidelines\n\n- Use tools judiciously as each call consumes Flow Action Credits\n- Consider alternatives before using credit-consuming tools\n- Plan multi-step operations to minimize tool usage\n- Analyze previous responses to optimize future credit usage\n- Develop strategies for credit-efficient operations\n- Implement hybrid approaches combining local tools with AI analysis\n- Create custom scripts for frequently performed operations",
